## Type Annotations — Contracts the Compiler Enforces

When you write `displayName: string`, you create a **compile-time contract**. The TypeScript compiler checks every call site against this contract before your code ever runs.

This is fundamentally different from JavaScript, where `formatWelcome(42)` would silently produce `"Welcome back, 42!"` — a bug that only surfaces in production when a user sees their numeric ID instead of their name.

```typescript
// The annotation is a contract:
function formatWelcome(displayName: string): string {
  return `Welcome back, ${displayName}!`;
}

// The compiler checks every call:
formatWelcome(user.name);  // string → string ✓
formatWelcome(user.id);    // number → string ✗ COMPILE ERROR
```

### The Key Insight

Type errors are not bugs — they are **prevented bugs**. Every red squiggly line is a runtime error that will never happen.

### Return Types

The `: string` after the parentheses declares the return type. If your function accidentally returns `undefined` in some branch, the compiler catches it:

```typescript
function getUser(id: number): User {
  if (id < 0) return; // ERROR: undefined is not User
}
```

