## Interfaces

An interface is a **structural contract** — it defines the exact shape an object must have.

```typescript
interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  phone?: string;   // ? means optional
  readonly createdAt: Date;  // readonly means immutable
}
```

### Optional Properties (`?`)

When an API field is sometimes present, `?` tells TypeScript: this property might be `undefined`. The compiler then forces you to check before using it:

```typescript
// UNSAFE — might be undefined:
user.phone.replace('+', '00');

// SAFE — compiler-enforced check:
if (user.phone) {
  user.phone.replace('+', '00');
}

// SAFE — optional chaining:
user.phone?.replace('+', '00');
```

### Structural Typing (Duck Typing)

TypeScript uses **structural** typing, not nominal. If an object has all the required properties, it satisfies the interface — regardless of how it was created:

```typescript
interface Point { x: number; y: number }

// This works even though we never said "implements Point":
const p = { x: 10, y: 20 };
function draw(point: Point) { /* ... */ }
draw(p); // ✓ — p has x and y, both numbers
```

expandableSections.content:
**Interfaces** can be extended (`extends`) and merged (declaration merging). **Type aliases** support unions (`|`), intersections (`&`), and mapped types. Rule of thumb: use interfaces for object shapes you expect others to extend; use type aliases for unions, primitives, and computed types.

```typescript
// Interface — extendable:
interface Animal { name: string }
interface Dog extends Animal { breed: string }

// Type alias — unions:
type Result = Success | Failure;
type ID = string | number;
```

`readonly` prevents reassignment after creation. It's compile-time only (no runtime enforcement), but it catches mutation bugs early:

```typescript
interface Config {
  readonly apiUrl: string;
  readonly maxRetries: number;
}

const config: Config = { apiUrl: 'https://api.example.com', maxRetries: 3 };
config.apiUrl = 'http://evil.com'; // COMPILE ERROR
```

`Readonly<T>` makes ALL properties readonly: `const frozen: Readonly<User> = user;`

