## Discriminated Unions

This is arguably TypeScript's most important pattern. You create separate interfaces with a **literal tag** property, then combine them with `|`. TypeScript can narrow the type by checking the tag:

```typescript
interface SuccessResponse {
  status: 'success';       // literal type — not just any string
  data: User;
}

interface ErrorResponse {
  status: 'error';         // different literal
  message: string;
  code: number;
}

type ApiResponse = SuccessResponse | ErrorResponse;

function handleResponse(res: ApiResponse) {
  if (res.status === 'success') {
    // TypeScript KNOWS res is SuccessResponse here
    console.log(res.data.name);  // ✓ safe
  } else {
    // TypeScript KNOWS res is ErrorResponse here
    console.log(res.message);    // ✓ safe
  }
}
```

### Why This Matters

This pattern models **real-world data perfectly**. APIs return different shapes depending on success/failure. Payment systems return different objects for each status. State machines have different valid properties per state.

### The Three Requirements

1. **Shared property** with literal types (the discriminant)
2. **Union** of the interfaces (`type X = A | B | C`)
3. **Narrowing check** on the discriminant property

### Real-World Examples

```typescript
// Redux actions:
type Action = 
  | { type: 'ADD_TODO'; payload: string }
  | { type: 'TOGGLE_TODO'; payload: number }
  | { type: 'DELETE_TODO'; payload: number };

// WebSocket messages:
type WSMessage =
  | { event: 'connected'; sessionId: string }
  | { event: 'message'; from: string; text: string }
  | { event: 'error'; code: number; reason: string };
```

expandableSections.content:
TypeScript can verify you handled every case in a discriminated union:

```typescript
function handleAction(action: Action) {
  switch (action.type) {
    case 'ADD_TODO': return addTodo(action.payload);
    case 'TOGGLE_TODO': return toggleTodo(action.payload);
    // Forgot DELETE_TODO!
    default:
      const _exhaustive: never = action;
      // ERROR: Type '{ type: "DELETE_TODO"; payload: number }'
      // is not assignable to type 'never'
  }
}
```

The `never` type means 'this should be unreachable'. If you miss a case, the compiler tells you.

