## Typing Async Code

Every `async` function returns a `Promise<T>` where T is the resolved value type:

```typescript
async function getUser(id: string): Promise<User> {
  const res = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);
  return res.json() as Promise<User>;
}
```

### The fetch() Problem

`fetch().json()` returns `Promise<any>` because the runtime doesn't know what shape the JSON has. You must tell TypeScript:

```typescript
// Generic wrapper:
async function fetchJson<T>(url: string): Promise<T> {
  const res = await fetch(url);
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);
  return res.json() as T;
}
const user = await fetchJson<User>('/api/user/1');
```

### Error Handling with Discriminated Unions

```typescript
type Result<T> = 
  | { ok: true; data: T }
  | { ok: false; error: string };

async function safeFetch<T>(url: string): Promise<Result<T>> {
  try {
    const res = await fetch(url);
    if (!res.ok) return { ok: false, error: `HTTP ${res.status}` };
    const data = await res.json() as T;
    return { ok: true, data };
  } catch (e) {
    return { ok: false, error: String(e) };
  }
}
```

This combines **discriminated unions** + **generics** + **async** — three patterns you've learned.

expandableSections.content:
Type assertions (`as T`) trust blindly. For real safety, validate at runtime:

```typescript
import { z } from 'zod';

const UserSchema = z.object({
  id: z.number(),
  name: z.string(),
  email: z.string().email(),
});
type User = z.infer<typeof UserSchema>;

async function fetchUser(id: string): Promise<User> {
  const json = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`).then(r => r.json());
  return UserSchema.parse(json); // Throws if shape doesn't match
}
```

Compile-time types AND runtime validation.

