## Utility Types

TypeScript ships with generic types that **transform** existing types:

| Utility | Effect | Use Case |
|---------|--------|----------|
| `Partial<T>` | All properties optional | PATCH/update payloads |
| `Required<T>` | All properties required | Ensure completeness |
| `Pick<T, K>` | Select specific properties | API response subsets |
| `Omit<T, K>` | Remove specific properties | Hide internal fields |
| `Record<K, V>` | Key-value mapping | Dictionaries, lookups |
| `Readonly<T>` | All properties readonly | Immutable config |

### Real-World Usage

```typescript
interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  passwordHash: string;
  createdAt: Date;
}

// API response (hide internals):
type PublicUser = Omit<User, 'passwordHash'>;

// Update payload (optional, no id/createdAt):
type UpdateUser = Partial<Omit<User, 'id' | 'createdAt'>>;

// Creation payload:
type CreateUser = Omit<User, 'id' | 'createdAt'>;
```

### How They Work: Mapped Types

```typescript
// Partial is defined as:
type Partial<T> = {
  [P in keyof T]?: T[P];
};
// Loops over each property P in T, makes it optional (?)
```

expandableSections.content:
```typescript
// Make specific properties required:
type RequireFields<T, K extends keyof T> = T & Required<Pick<T, K>>;

type UserWithEmail = RequireFields<Partial<User>, 'email'>;
// All optional, but email is required
```

```typescript
type Status = 'active' | 'inactive' | 'banned' | 'pending';

type ActiveStatus = Extract<Status, 'active' | 'pending'>;
// Result: 'active' | 'pending'

type SafeStatus = Exclude<Status, 'banned'>;
// Result: 'active' | 'inactive' | 'pending'
```

Extract keeps matches, Exclude removes them.

